WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.330 --> 00:00:03.450
- Talking about the problems with methane.

00:00:03.450 --> 00:00:07.890
So a blade of grass tips over and dies,

00:00:07.890 --> 00:00:10.080
and it rots, it creates methane.

00:00:10.080 --> 00:00:11.910
A cow can eat that same blade of grass,

00:00:11.910 --> 00:00:14.700
and it produces the same exact methane.

00:00:14.700 --> 00:00:16.530
So that's like high school biology.

00:00:16.530 --> 00:00:19.440
However, when it's discussed in Congress,

00:00:19.440 --> 00:00:23.400
it's cows eating grass are
destroying the environment,

00:00:23.400 --> 00:00:26.400
even though cows eating
grass are the environment.

00:00:26.400 --> 00:00:30.210
So the whole argument's sort of false.

00:00:30.210 --> 00:00:33.960
And now we have pharmaceutical
companies that are supporting

00:00:33.960 --> 00:00:36.510
and sort of the AMA is
also supporting this,

00:00:36.510 --> 00:00:39.840
this idea of, because
they like sick people.

00:00:39.840 --> 00:00:41.820
They make great customers.

00:00:41.820 --> 00:00:44.970
So it's two forces that are pushing

00:00:44.970 --> 00:00:47.400
to make the most
nutritious food available,

00:00:47.400 --> 00:00:52.290
that being animal protein,
either illegal or sanctioned

00:00:52.290 --> 00:00:54.603
or over-taxed or something like that.

00:00:55.440 --> 00:00:56.583
What can be done?

00:00:58.170 --> 00:01:00.813
Like how can we protect the beef industry?

00:01:02.940 --> 00:01:04.443
- You know, I think what,

00:01:05.820 --> 00:01:09.570
you know, I think there's a new crop

00:01:09.570 --> 00:01:13.320
of environmentalists who are understanding

00:01:13.320 --> 00:01:18.320
the importance of keeping
animals on the land.

00:01:18.780 --> 00:01:21.527
And you know, I kind of grew up

00:01:21.527 --> 00:01:24.123
in that area because I was,

00:01:25.350 --> 00:01:29.670
I spent a lot of my career
suing factory farms.

00:01:29.670 --> 00:01:32.070
And I've probably sued Smithfield more

00:01:32.070 --> 00:01:36.253
than any other attorney,
Tyson's, Purdue, Bo Pilgrim,

00:01:38.220 --> 00:01:40.770
all the big, you know, Wendell Murphy,

00:01:40.770 --> 00:01:44.370
all of the big mass, you know, CAFO,

00:01:44.370 --> 00:01:46.748
concentrated animal feed operations.

00:01:46.748 --> 00:01:47.808
- Sure.

00:01:47.808 --> 00:01:52.080
- And what's happened is the
transformation of land use.

00:01:52.080 --> 00:01:54.030
And I think more and more,

00:01:54.030 --> 00:01:56.744
and so they're now, you know,

00:01:56.744 --> 00:02:01.320
dousing the fields with pesticides.

00:02:01.320 --> 00:02:04.350
And we're not doing what,

00:02:04.350 --> 00:02:07.950
and with carbon-based chemicals,

00:02:07.950 --> 00:02:10.260
you know, fertilizers.
- Yes.

00:02:10.260 --> 00:02:12.690
- And what we've learned is
it's destroying the soils.

00:02:12.690 --> 00:02:15.850
And that the best thing that
you can do for the climate

00:02:17.014 --> 00:02:22.014
is to have wholesome, rich soils.

00:02:22.170 --> 00:02:23.310
- Right.
- And the best way

00:02:23.310 --> 00:02:27.060
to aerate the soil and to make sure

00:02:27.060 --> 00:02:29.940
that it's healthy is by
having ungulates on it

00:02:29.940 --> 00:02:33.660
who are tearing up the
earth with their hooves,

00:02:33.660 --> 00:02:35.880
who are spreading manure on that soil

00:02:35.880 --> 00:02:37.530
and returning soil health.

00:02:37.530 --> 00:02:40.217
And when it's a healthy soil,

00:02:40.217 --> 00:02:42.450
you're absorbing a lot more carbon.

00:02:42.450 --> 00:02:46.877
So if your primary concern is carbon,

00:02:48.270 --> 00:02:50.400
it solves that problem,
but it also does a lot

00:02:50.400 --> 00:02:52.170
of other god things for the environment.

00:02:52.170 --> 00:02:53.320
It helps

00:02:56.490 --> 00:03:00.340
rainwater to permeate the land

00:03:01.440 --> 00:03:03.990
rather than to run off across the surface.

00:03:03.990 --> 00:03:06.420
And you know, which is
very, very destructive,

00:03:06.420 --> 00:03:10.860
not only to soils, but also
the water systems, et cetera.

00:03:10.860 --> 00:03:14.100
So I think there is sort of a new,

00:03:14.100 --> 00:03:17.730
and when I started making these
arguments back in the '90s,

00:03:17.730 --> 00:03:19.500
they were very novel arguments.

00:03:19.500 --> 00:03:21.690
People at that time were, you know,

00:03:21.690 --> 00:03:26.550
were subsumed in the
carbon-only orthodoxy.

00:03:26.550 --> 00:03:27.383
That's the, you know,

00:03:27.383 --> 00:03:28.770
only important issue.
- Right.

00:03:28.770 --> 00:03:32.340
- And I think more and more
environmentalists coming up,

00:03:32.340 --> 00:03:34.743
including, you know, one
of the leaders of that,

00:03:35.850 --> 00:03:38.370
who I've met is a guy
called Charles Eisenstein,

00:03:38.370 --> 00:03:42.273
who is the messaging
director for my campaign.

00:03:43.680 --> 00:03:46.080
You know, I think you've
got a whole bunch of people

00:03:46.080 --> 00:03:49.890
in this campaign who
are very much in favor

00:03:49.890 --> 00:03:52.500
of regenerative agriculture,

00:03:52.500 --> 00:03:55.890
very much against the
idea of synthetic foods.

00:03:55.890 --> 00:03:57.060
- Right.

00:03:57.060 --> 00:04:00.300
- And other, you know, eating insects

00:04:00.300 --> 00:04:01.770
and all the other weird ideas

00:04:01.770 --> 00:04:03.840
that are coming from-
- Yeah.

00:04:03.840 --> 00:04:06.210
- From the corporate kleptocracy.

00:04:06.210 --> 00:04:08.520
- Practically unusable
protein by the human body,

00:04:08.520 --> 00:04:09.930
but nobody really talks about.
- Yeah.

00:04:09.930 --> 00:04:11.340
Nobody even knows what's in it.

00:04:11.340 --> 00:04:14.163
I mean, nobody really even
knows what's in real meat.

00:04:15.450 --> 00:04:16.614
You know, I mean-
- Yeah.

00:04:16.614 --> 00:04:17.610
- There's so much of it-
- The essential amino acids,

00:04:17.610 --> 00:04:19.890
the vitamin B12, like you can't survive-

00:04:19.890 --> 00:04:20.723
- Right.
- For more

00:04:20.723 --> 00:04:22.260
than seven or eight years with out.

00:04:22.260 --> 00:04:23.190
- Yeah.
- Now fortunately

00:04:23.190 --> 00:04:25.650
for vegans, statistically,
they do eat meat

00:04:25.650 --> 00:04:26.610
when they're drunk.

00:04:26.610 --> 00:04:28.020
So they'll probably
(Robert laughing)

00:04:28.020 --> 00:04:29.820
do okay long-term,

00:04:29.820 --> 00:04:33.090
but we need to keep
healthy food on the shelves

00:04:33.090 --> 00:04:34.080
of the grocery store.

00:04:34.080 --> 00:04:35.880
- Yeah.
- It is so important

00:04:35.880 --> 00:04:38.970
for America to understand
that you understand this.

00:04:38.970 --> 00:04:40.380
- Yeah.

00:04:40.380 --> 00:04:42.720
Well, done.
- Awesome.

00:04:42.720 --> 00:04:43.989
Thank you so much.

00:04:43.989 --> 00:04:45.030
(Robert laughing)

00:04:45.030 --> 00:04:47.483
- I love that tie.
- That's it, that's all I got.

